<HEADLINE>
<P>
PERSONAL HEALTH; WORKERS CAN SLICE HEALTH CARE COSTS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By WASHINGTON POST 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Employees who improve health habits can reduce their company's health care 
costs, according to a nine-year study at the University of Michigan. The 
average age of participants was 44; 75% were men. 
</P>
<P>
 Based on habits and health, participants were classified as high risk or low 
risk and were offered smoking cessation, weight reduction and stress management 
classes. 
</P>
<P>
 During the next six years, researchers tracking medical insurance claims found 
that high-risk workers in 1985 who were low risk by 1988 had lower claims from 
1988-90, for an annual savings of $618. 
</P>
<P>
 Employees who remained high risk saw claims rise more than $500. 
</P>
<P>
 Low-risk employees' costs were the same. But low-risk workers who slipped to 
high risk saw claims more than double. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
