<HEADLINE>
<P>
FDA ALLOWS LABELS FOR MILK FROM COWS NOT GIVEN HORMONE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By Associated Press 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Stores and dairies can label milk as coming from cows not treated with a 
controversial new hormone, but the labels can't suggest the milk is any safer 
than that from treated animals, the government said Monday. 
</P>
<P>
 In guidelines to be published today, the Food and Drug Administration said 
companies may label milk, ice cream and other dairy products as coming from 
"cows not treated with" recombinant bovine somatotropin. 
</P>
<P>
 But the label also would have to carry a statement like, "No significant 
difference has been shown between milk derived from rbST-treated and 
non-rbST-treated cows," the agency said. 
</P>
<P>
 The genetically engineered version of the naturally occurring hormone went on 
the market Friday. 
</P>
<P>
 The agency said labels could not carry the claim that milk is "bST-free" 
because the hormone occurs naturally in milk. 
</P>
</TEXT>
