<HEADLINE>
<P>
$1-MILLION PRIZE IS OFFERED FOR WAYS TO TEST FOR 2 SEX DISEASES 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From a Times Staff Writer 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 The Rockefeller Foundation Monday announced a $1-million prize -- one of the 
largest in medicine -- for development of an easy, low cost diagnostic test for 
two sexually transmitted diseases which strike more than 75 million people 
worldwide. 
</P>
<P>
 The diseases, chlamydia and gonorrhea, can be cured relatively easily with 
antibiotics if discovered, but can lead to serious complications, including 
infant blindness, if left untreated. Current methods of diagnosis are 
unsuitable because they require equipment unavailable in many areas of the 
world, and cost about $12 a patient, a prohibitive price in developing nations, 
the foundation said in announcing the award. 
</P>
<P>
 Entries for the prize will be accepted for five years or until a winner is 
named. 
</P>
