<HEADLINE>
<P>
MISGUIDED TO FIRMER GROUND 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Regarding the article in Valley Business on Feb. 1 that "Some buyers from the 
San Fernando Valley seek firmer ground in Antelope Valley." . . . The article 
seems to say the people wanting to move there think that Palmdale is 
seismically safer than the San Fernando Valley.This seems ignorant because most 
of the new houses in Palmdale are within a mile or two of the San Andreas 
Fault. Even though the houses there may be built better, people are going to be 
shaken a lot more when that fault moves. I think it's because of what we have 
built over and around us that may fall on, or explode next to us, that makes 
many people fearful of earthquakes (myself included) and want to move away from 
them. But I would not move next to the largest fault in California. 
</P>
<P>
 TOM NORR 
</P>
<P>
 Monrovia 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Letter to the Editor 
</P>
</TYPE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> LA020894-0261 </DOCNO>
<DOCID> 011614 </DOCID>
<SOURCE>
<P>
 Los Angeles Times 
</P>
</SOURCE>
